               <interp inst="t18770917-748" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18770917"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18770917-748" type="date" value="18770917"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18770917-748-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-748-18770917 t18770917-748-offence-1 t18770917-748-verdict-1"></join>
               <p>748. <persName id="def1-748-18770917" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-748-18770917" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-748-18770917" type="age" value="40"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-748-18770917" type="surname" value="PFEIFFER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-748-18770917" type="given" value="MARTIN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">MARTIN PFEIFFER</hi> (40)</persName>
                  <rs id="t18770917-748-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18770917-748-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18770917-748-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp>, Stealing 50 Napoleons and other coins, the property of <persName id="t18770917-name-546" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-546" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-546" type="surname" value="BERGMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-546" type="given" value="WILHELM"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-546" type="occupation" value="merchant"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18770917-748-offence-1 t18770917-name-546"></join>Wiihelm Bergman</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BESLEY</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CROOME</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">conducted the Prosecution; and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. STRAIGHT</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">the Defence.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18770917-name-547" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-547" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-547" type="surname" value="BERGMAN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-547" type="given" value="WILHELM"></interp>WILHELM BERGMAN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">through, an interpreter</hi>). I am a merchant and live in Poland, I bad been in England five months in May, or June, 1877—I do not know whether that was the date of my going or of my coming back—I do not know a word of English; I corresponded with the prisoner before I left here—I arrived in London again on Wednesday, 8th August, and put up at the hotel Causier, 23, Broad Street, Bloomsbury, and telegraphed to the prisoner announcing my arrival in London—he came to my hotel the same night about 6 o'clock, and I had a conversation with him in Polish—he told me he should be able to purchase some Chamois skins—he did not say who from, only that he would call next day about them—he said that to-morrow about noon we should go to the merchant, but did not give me the merchant's address—about 11 o'clock next morning his wife called and I went with her to 43, Clifton Crescent, Peckham, where they live—we went into the dining-room where I saw the prisoner in bed, he said that he had caught cold and had sent for the merchant who would be there in two hours—I remained there, and at the end of that time Mrs. Pfeiffer came upstairs and said that the merchant had arrived—the prisoner put his clothes on and went down with me to the merchant, whom I had never seen before—I have since pointed him out at the Cafe Monico, in Piccadilly, to Mr. Woolf; his name is David Von Hand—the would be merchant produced a little bag in which there was one Chamois skin as a sample, and they conversed in English which I did not understand—I examined one skin and made a bargain for</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187709170231"></xptr>
               <p>170 dozen of them, which amounted to 450<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. English—Pfeiffer asked me twice to give the money to the merchant—I said that as I had the pleasure of seeing the merchant for the first time in my life and did not know him, I would rather not part with my money until I got the skins—they conversed together and Pfeiffer sent out for some brandy, and we had a glass together—it was arranged for Pfeiffer and the merchant to come to my hotel, and we were all to go to the warehouse and inspect the skins—no address was given where the skins were—Pfeiffer told me that I could trust any amount of money with the merchant, that he had had transactions with him to a very large amount—after several attempts made by Pfeiffer to induce me to part with my money to the merchant, he told me to give it to him, and I gave him a deposit, for which this receipt produced was written; the body of it is in my writing and the signature is Pfeiffer's—the figures on the receipt stamp are mine—I gave him 2,200 Prussian bank-notes, marks, and 1,000 francs in French gold. (<hi rend="italic">The receipt as translated was for</hi> 2,200 <hi rend="italic">Prussian bank-notes, and</hi> 1,000 <hi rend="italic">francs; as a deposit for the purchase of</hi> 130 <hi rend="italic">dozen Chamois skins; to be returned if the bargain was not concluded, and signed Martin Pfeiffer</hi>, 10<hi rend="italic">th August</hi>, 1877.) The date is a mistake, it took place on Thursday, the 9th—the next day Pfeiffer came to my hotel without the merchant—he said that the merchant had not come, no doubt something had happened to him and I must be quite easy, very likely I should see him to-morrow—next day Pfeiffer came again without the merchant and said that most likely very important business had kept him from coming on so slight an affair—I smelt that the business was not right and said "This is not <hi rend="italic">bond-fide</hi> business, it looks like a swindle"—on the following Sunday I went to Pfeiffer at Peckham, and told him to go to the—merchant—I said "I do not want any skins, give me my money back"—he said "I have not got the money, I gave it to the merchant"—being Sunday he said "We cannot go and see him, the merchant does not live in. London, he is only a travelling merchant"—we went on that very Sunday to look after him in a public-house or coffee-house—he told me that generally the merchant was there about 6 o'clock in the evening and very likely we might meet him there, but the place was shut up—Pfeiffer then told me he should try and find him to-morrow, and for certain he would come to me on the Monday, and said that he was not able to find him—I asked for the merchant's home and residence; he told me he did not know it himself, that he only met him in that coffee-house—he had said on Monday that the merchant was a Frenchman—I saw Pfeiffer every day after that—I returned to Nottingham on Sunday, 19th August, and returned on the following Tuesday with Mr. Woolf—with the exception of those days I saw Pfeiffer every day until I gave him in custody—I kept secret that I wanted to arrest differ; I did not see him after the 16th—I went to Dover on Thursday, the 16th, that was the Thursday before I went to Nottingham—the prisoner went with me to the station, and was with me up to the starting of the train—I paid for my ticket; I asked the prisoner for my money, and he said I should have it when I got into the carriage—when the train was going to start I asked him for the 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I told him I was going to Poland, but my intention was to keep secret in London that I might arrest him—I did not. get the 5<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I wished him good-bye, the train started, and he stopped at the station—he was taken custody on Wednesday night, August 22nd, after which Mrs. Pfeiffer gave me a card of Mr. Kipps, of Bermondsey—I went there on Saturday, 25th August with Mr. Woolf, who spoke to Mr. Kipps in.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187709170232"></xptr>
               <p>English—I had already taken out a warrant—I gave evidence twice, once before I saw Mr. Kipps, and once afterwards.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> I had a shop of all sorts in Poland—I have never had a business transaction with the prisoner; he went with me about business but I did not do business with him before—I went with Mrs. Pfeiffer to Gatti's restaurant, and from there to the Canterbury Music Hall after dinner—she left me there and went home alone—the word "Chamois" is not in this receipt, it is "Skins"—it was written at Charing Cross Station, not at Peckham—Ffeiffer said he was rather unwell and wanted to take fresh air, and asked me to go for a stroll, and he gave me this receipt after a couple of hours' walking about; but I was at his house from 12 o'clock till 4.30—the would-be merchant stayed with us about an hour and a half, and when he left I was left alone with Pfeiffer for a couple of hours longer—I went out with Pfeiffer about 5 o'clock—he went home from Charing Cross about 7 o'clock and I met Mrs. Pfeiffer about 7.30—I said before the Magistrate that he gave me the receipt marked A at the time—that is true; he gave it me the same day, at Charing Cross—I pressed him to give it to me, and he said "Well, let us go to the station and I will give it you"—I did not know that Gatti's is close by—this is very likely the first time I have mentioned its being written at Charing Cross—they did not ask me the question before the Magistrate—it was not written on the 16th—after the conversation between Mr. Woolf and Mr. Kipps, Mr. Woolf told me that Kipps was willing to give 200<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. for Mr. Pfeiffer—we remained there half an hour.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> Pfeiffer gave me the card with Kipps' address, and said he would see me—Mr. Woolf spoke to Kipps in English, and he told me that Mr. Kipps was willing to give me 150<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. back of the money, and 50<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. for expenses incurred, to get Pfeiffer out of prison—Woolf told me I must go to a solicitor—I did not propose any compromise through Woolf—he told me the matter was already in the Justices' hands, and the best thing would be for him to go to the solicitor of this man.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18770917-name-548" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-548" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-548" type="surname" value="HAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-548" type="given" value="DAVID VON"></interp>DAVID VON HAND</persName>
                  </hi>. I keep an hotel at 23, Broad Street, Golden Square, about three minutes' walk from the Hotel de Versailles—four or five days after Bergman arrived, and after 13th August, Stanislas, an interpreter, was pointed out to me at the Cafe Monaco, and I saw him every day at Charing Cross Station—he takes people from there to hotels, and I think he has something to do with the Hotel de Versailles—he is a Pole—I have not seen him since the prosecutor has been at the police-court, but the evening afterwards I saw him with a number of gentlemen at the Argyle—I have since been at the place where I used to see him, and have not seen him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> I have known Stanislas more than two years at Charing Cross Station.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18770917-name-549" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-549" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-549" type="surname" value="WOOLF"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-549" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM WOOLF</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a Pole, and live in Nottingham—I am not in business now—on Sunday, 19th August, Bergman came down to me and on Tuesday, 21st, I came to London with him—we went to the Cafe Monarco the same evening with Mr. Von Hand—Bergman pointed out a man to Mr. Von Hand and gave me this card of Mr. Kipps (<hi rend="italic">produced</hi>)—I went to Mr. Kipps on the Saturday with Bergman, and told him all the circumstances——he said that Mrs. Pfeiffer had been, to him and wished him to come to some arrangement—he asked me what arrangement we could come to—I said "I do not know that we can come to any arrangement ourselves, I think the solicitors will have to come to an arrangement"—he said "No, we can manage</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187709170233"></xptr>
               <p>that ourselves, she suggested to me to give you a draft at a month"—he did not say for how much—I asked him what a draft was—he said "An accept<lb></lb>ance like these," showing me some—he asked me what we should be satisfied with—I said "It comes to 160<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. and the expenses will be enormous"—he suggested 50<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. and I persuaded Bergman to take that and not prosecute, provided the solicitor would agree to it—I had employed Messrs. Huckley and Washington before the warrant was taken out—I said "I cannot go and liberate Mr. Pfeiffer, I cannot see how it can be done without solicitors, go and see your solicitor and take him to see Mr. Pfeiffer, and I shall go and see Pfeiffer and let you know"—I said that I was going to Nottingham, and he gave me a piece of paper stating where he would meet me and give me an answer—he came at the appointed time at the railway, station and said that the solicitor advised him not to do it—I had not known Kipps before.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> As a matter of fact 200<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. was the sum to be paid, and I expected Bergman to accept it, subject to the approval of the Court—I took Bergman to Messrs. Huckley and Washington.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18770917-name-550" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-550" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-550" type="surname" value="STEVENS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-550" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES STEVENS</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">Detective Officer P</hi>). I took the prisoner in Cromer Road, Peckham, on a warrant—I said "I shall take you in custody for defrauding Mr. Bergman of certain notes"—he said "Yes, I had the money, I gave him a receipt"—I said "There is a warrant for conspiracy as well as fraud"—he said that there was no one with him, he himself was the merchant and he should let him have the skins when they were ready—I have tried to find Stanislas, and have circulated his name in the "Police Gazette."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> The warrant was for conspiracy with another man un<lb></lb>known.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Witnesses for the Defence.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18770917-name-551" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-551" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-551" type="surname" value="KEWICSESKI"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-551" type="given" value="ANTONE"></interp>ANTONE KEWICSESKI</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">through an interpreter</hi>). I am the prisoner's father-in-law—I live with him and my daughter at 43, Clifton Crescent, Peckham—my wife lives with us—on 9th August the prisoner was ill—the prosecutor came between noon and 1 o'clock, and remained till about 4 o'clock—no other man came into the house while he was there—when he left my daughter the prisoner's wife went with him—the prisoner did not go out, because he was not well, he did not leave the house—Mrs. Pfeiffer came back after midnight.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CROOME</hi>. There are six rooms in the house—I was not in the same room with the prisoner and Bergman—they were in the front parlour and I was in the basement underneath, with my wife—I did not go out all day, nor did the prisoner—I saw Bergman leave—a Mr. David came at 4 o'clock.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> There is a little garden in front of the house, and I can see everybody who comes up the path.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18770917-name-552" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-552" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-552" type="surname" value="MORRIS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-552" type="given" value="DAVID"></interp>DAVID MORRIS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am manager to a tailor, and live at 4, Commercial Road, Bermondsey—on 9th August, I went to the prisoner's house about 6.30 p.m., and stayed with him three-quarters of an hour—he was in bed—it is not true that he was at Charing Cross between 6 and 7 o'clock.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> I have known the prisoner about two years, and frequently go there in the evening—I was first asked to come and give evidence when I received a letter dated September 14th—nothing passed on the 9th to make me remember the date—I saw Mr. Kewickeski there—I do not know whether Mrs. Pfeiffer was at home.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18770917-name-553" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-553" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-553" type="surname" value="LORENZO"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-553" type="given" value="JAMOLI"></interp>JAMOLI LORENZO</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a waiter at Gatti's Restaurant, Adelaide Street, Strand—on 9th August, about 7 p.m., I saw Mrs. Pfeiffer, Mr. Bergman,</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187709170234"></xptr>
               <p>and a little boy there—they left about 7.30, or 7.35 at the latest—they had something to eat there.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> I knew Mrs. Pfeiffer, she often came there—I was first spoken to about two weeks ago about giving evidence—there are a great many people at Gatti's in the course of a day—I had never seen them together before—when they asked me I remembered seeing them—they had some chops.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18770917-name-554" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-554" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-554" type="surname" value="TAYLOR"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-554" type="given" value="EMMA"></interp>EMMA TAYLOR</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at 36, Mark's Road, and am employed at the South Eastern Railway Station—it is part of my duty to clean out the waiting-room—I was there early one morning, just about the time the Paris mail starts—I do not know the day of the month—I saw the prisoner and prosecutor about 7 o'clock, or a little after, in the general waiting-room—they called for pen and ink, which I gave them, and left it with them—I did not see whether anything was written—I am prepared to swear that it was before 10 a. m.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> I had never seen Pfeiffer before—I saw him next in Horsemonger Lane about three weeks ago—the solicitor spoke to me about seeing him—it is not uncommon for pen and ink to be called for—I was very busy—a gentleman came and asked me if I remembered seeing a gentleman on this morning there, and then I remembered it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> I picked out the prisoner at Horsemonger Lane from ten or twelve others—I do not remain there all day, I generally leave about 10 o'clock, when my work is done—I am not there of an evening, I am only a charwoman.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18770917-name-555" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-555" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-555" type="surname" value="KIPPS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-555" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD KIPPS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a tanner, of 94, Bermondsey—I have known the prisoner six or seven years; he is a respectable, trustworthy man—I have had transactions with him in selling skins for shoe manufacture—he was in my employ six years ago, and afterwards set up as a leather dresser—I do not know whether he is able to carry out contracts for the purchase of skins—I have done business with him within two years, and have a bill of his running now, and should be willing to have another, I have so much confidence in his honesty—to my surprise one day, Mrs. Pfeiffer called on me to say that her husband was in trouble, for conspiracy and fraud; would I be bail for him, and she called again on 25th August and asked me if I would refund the money for him—on 25th August Mr. Woolf and Mr. Bergman called and Mr. Woolf asked me if I would pay the money for him—I said not unless I knew the facts of the case first—he said that Mr. Pfeiffer had had the money to execute a contract, and had failed to do so, and they could neither get the goods nor the money—I asked what was the amount, he said 160<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. and 80<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. expenses—I said it was exhorbitant to expect 80<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., and they reduced it to 40<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.—I placed that on paper, but previously to that I said that it would be wrong for me to compromise the matter, the best way would be to ask the solicitor's opinion—I afterwards met the prisoner at the station for Nottingham, and told him I could not do it.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined.</hi> He left me two or three years ago, but I did not lose sight of him—he frequently called and bought goods—I do not know whether he was carrying on business at the time he was taken—I did not give Woolf a bill for 200<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.; I made no proposition, the proposition came from him—I have been outside the Court while this case has been proceeding—I have had a very few words of conversation about the matter—somebody came out and told me to go away from the place, but said nothing with regard to the evidence I was to give, except that I was to hold myself</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="187709170235"></xptr>
               <p>in readiness, and that he was pleased I had come here—I bad not a lengthened conversation with the solicitor's clerk; there is no truth in it—I was to give the bill for 200<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., and they would accept it, that was to be a settlement of the claim.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Re-examined.</hi> It is not true that anyone suggested to me a word of the evidence which I have given.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18770917-name-556" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-556" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-556" type="surname" value="GALLOW"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18770917-name-556" type="given" value="ADOLPH DE"></interp>ADOLPH DE GALLOW</persName>
                  </hi>. I am clerk to Messrs. Parker and Bordman—I did not go outside the Court and communicate with the last witness—none of these witnesses were examined before the Magistrate.</p>
